{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_parsifal_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280608658/1957112701/1022.xml":{"full_text":"Eisenhower Reported\nIn Excellent Spirits\nContinued From Firct Puce\nto rule out completely the pos\nefbllity that Mr. Biaenhower\nmay decide to attend the NATO\nsummit meeting beginning in\nParis December 16. as he had\nplanned, if his recovery goes\nquickly.\nIt was announced late yes\nterday that the United States\nhad informed the NATO coun\ncil that \u2018lt is to be assumed\u201d!\nthe President's illness will make j\nit Impossible for him to attend. j\nThis Government asked the\nNATO council to decide\nwhether the meeting still would 1 1\nbe held on a heads-of-govern- i\nment level. i\nAwaits President's Decision j1\nMr. Hagerty said that when 1\nthe council made that decision.\nIt would be up to the President j\nto decide who would represent!\nthe United States.\nIt is generally assumed that\nVice President Nixon would go\nto the Paris meeting in Mr.\nEisenhower\u2019s place.\nBut when asked today if he:\nthought it \"in the realm of j'\npossibility.\u201d that the President!\nmight still go to Paris himself,\nMr. Hagerty said: \u201cI am notj\ngoing to speculate on that at\nall. 1 will wait and see the'\ndevelopments as they happen.\nI can\u2019t give you any defin\nitive answer on that at this\ntime.\u201d\nMr. Nixon. Secretary of State\nDulles and Attorney General\nRogers met In the White House\nduring the morning with some\nof the White House staff on\nwhat Mr. Hagerty described\nonly as \u201cWhite House\nbusiness.\u201d\nHe told reporters that of i\ncourse the question of the j\nNATO meeting was discussed\nduring Mr. Dulles\u2019 visit-.\nDerides Resignation Story\nWhen a reporter asked Mr.:\nHagerty\u2019s reaction to a sug\ngestion in London newspapers\nthat Mr. Eisenhower should\nresign in view of his illness,\nMr. Hagerty replied: \u201cJust say\nI laughed and haven\u2019t any\nreaction.\u201d\nAs to whether any major\nproblem requiring decision by\nthe President would be taken to\nhim now. Mr. Hagerty said \u201cMy\nfeeling would be yes.\u201d He ex\nplained that it would depend\non approval of the doctors,\npointing out that the Presi\ndent's work this morning was\ndone after he asked their per\nmission.\nMr. Eisenhower sat in an\neasy chair in his bedroom as he\ntalked with Gen. Goodpaster\nand signed the 12 documents\nthis morning, Mr. Hagerty\nsaid.\nThe President's own good\nspirits over his latest illness set\nthe tone for the whole White\nHouse staff. TTiere was little of\nthe tension apparent around\nthe White House today that was\nevident yesterday and such as\nmarked his previous heart at\ntack and ileitis operation.\n\u201cEverything is all right,\u201d\nGen. Snyder told reporters as\nTie entered the' White House\nthis morning.\nHis optimistic view wae in\u2019\nline with the latest report from\nneurological specialists that 1\nthe President\u2019s \u201cpresent dis-\nability is mild and transitory\nin nature.\u201d\nOutlook Called \"Excellent\u201d\nThe doctors reported yester\nday that chances for complete i\nrecovery of the President are 1\n\u201cexcellent.\u201d especially in view\nof the Improvement he has i\nshown since he was stricken' 1\nMonday afternoon.\nTne medical diagnosis was\nthat Mr. Eisenhower \u201csuffered\nan occlusion of a small branch\nof the middle cerebral artery j\non the left side.\u201d There were\nho indications of brain hemor-\nrhage.\nDr. Snyder told reporters this\nmorning that \"no doctor up to\nthis moment could tell if it is j\na stroke\u201d that the President\nsuffered because it could not be\ndetermined whether the blood\nstoppage was anything more j\nthan a vascular spasm. Ap-\nparently it was either that or a\nsmall clot.\nBesides a \u201cchill\u201d that caused 1\nhim to call for an extra blanket j\nand a hot water bottle when\nhe went to bed Monday after\nnoon. the President has shown 1\nno abnormal symptoms other 1\nthan a mild difficulty in speak- 1\ning, his doctors reported. And\nthis has been Improving.\nBoth Mr. Hagqrty and the 1\ndoctors reported his memory\nand reasoning powers are not\nAffected. jl\nAttended by Doctors\n1 A total of nine doctors, who 1\nhave been attending the Presi- 1\ndent and are consulting on the\ncase, agreed that he will require 1\nseveral weeks of rest and \u201csub- 1\nstantlally decreased activity.\u201d 1\nMr. Hagerty. who had been j\nin Paris arranging for the 1\nPresident\u2019s planned visit there.\nflew back to Washington late\nlast night and took over the\nJob of keeping the public in\nformed about the President\u2019s\ncondition that had been car-:!\nried on yesterday by Mrs. Anne i\nWheaton, associate press sec- i\nretary.\nMr. Hagerty\u2019s close relation-\nship with the President was re-\nfleeted Immediately in a flow of i\n[FOR MERCUrTi\ni IN ALEXANDRIA 8\nICKNTRAL MOTOR CO. I\n1201 Oronoco St. OV'. 3*1500\nALEXANDRIA\u2019S ONLY MERCURY DEALER I\nI. Hm Heart ts Alexandria\u20144 Block. Freni Kin f St. M\nm mm mum mum m,\nmore detailed news about his\ncondition and activities.\nNews Flow Quickens\nCalling reporters into his of\nfice at 8:18 a.m. today, Mr.\nHagerty apologized for being\nlate with his promised 8 am.\nreport, explaining that it was\nbecause the President had slept\nlate.\nHe read reporters a brief\nstatement on behalf of Dr.\nSnyder.\nThe statement follows:\n\"The President slept almost\ncontinuously throughout the\nnight. He awoke refreshed\nthis morning. He took his\nusual shower and shaved and\nhas just had a normal break\nfast.\u201d\nMr. Hagerty added that Mr.\nEisenhower went to bed about\n10 p.m., after watching tele-\nI vision with Mrs. Eisenhower\nifor about two hours, and slept\n'until about 7:40 am.\nFor breakfast. Mr. Hagerty\nreported .the President had\nhalf a grapefruit, creamed\nchipped beef, toast, honey and\nSanka.\nThe press secretary said he\nand Dr. Snyder talked with\nj the President for about 10\nminutes this morning, with\nMrs. Eisenhower joining them.\nMemory Appears Sound\nAsked if there was any im\npairment of the President's\nmemory. Mr. Hagerty smiled\nand said \u201cthere certainly did\nnot seem to be.\u201d He added\nthat in talking to him this\nmorning Mr. Eisenhower asked\nhim many things about old\nfriends in Paris.\nMr. Hagerty said Col. Walter\n|R. Tkach, assistant White\nHouse physician, and Capt.\nLorene Miller, an Army nurse\nattached to Walter Reed Hos\npital, were on duty through\nthe night.\nAttended Both Eisenhowers\nCapt. Miller was one of the\nPresident\u2019s nurses at Walter\nReed during his recuperation\nfrom his ileitis operation in\nJune, 1956. and also attended\nMrs. Eisenhower after her\nhysterectomy operation last\nsummer.\nThe fact that the President\nis suffering no disability except\nthe slight speech difficulty\nmakes his current illness much\nless of a crisis in government!\nthan was his ileitis attack or\nhis September, 1955 heart at\ntack. On both those occasions I\ni he was completely out of action\nfor varying periods.\nHis doctors agreed that his\ni heart is not involved in his\ni present illness. &nd that it has\ni no connection with the previous\nheart attack or ileitis.\nThe White House first an\nnounced at 3 p.m. yesterday\u2014\nnearly 21 hours after the ini-!\ntial disclosure that the Presi-\ndent had a \"chill\u201d\u2014that Mr.\nEisenhower had suffered a cere\nbral \u201cocclusion.\u201d Symptom*\nwere like those of a mild stroke,\nbut his doctors would not call It\nthat.\n\u201cUrn outlook for complete\nrecovery within a reasonable\nperiod of time la excellent,\u201d\naccording to the medical re\nport issued through Mrs.\nWheaton. The report was made\nby Gen Snyder, the President\u2019*\npersonal physician, and Gen.\nHeaton, commandant of Wal\nter Reed Army Hospital.\n\"Although the present con\ndition is mild and' is expected\nto be transitory in nature, it\nwill require a period of rest\nand substantially decreased ac\ntivity estimated at several\nweeks,\u201d they said.\nNo Hemorrhage InOlcated\nPhysical and neurological\nexamination yesterday morn\ning \u201cconfirms our original\ndiagnosis that the President\nsuffered an occlusion of a\nsmall branch of the middle\ncerebral artery on the left\nside,\u201d the doctors said. \"\u201cIt\ncannot \u2022be determined at this\ntime whether the condition\npresent is one of a small clot\nor a vascular spasm. All find\nings indicate no brain hemor\nrhage.\u201d\nThe optimistic prognosis ap\nparently was based largely on\nrapid improvement in the\nPresident\u2019s speech.\nThe medical report said the\nPresident complained of a chill\nat 1 p.m. Monday when he re\nturned to the White House\nafter escorting King Mohame\u2019d\nV of Morocco from the airport.\nHe lay down to rest in his\ndressing room, asking for an\nextra blanket and a hot water\nbottle.\nMr. Eisenhower returned to\nhis office at 2:40 p.m. Monday\nafter a rest and lunch, the\nreport continued. He did not\nfeel well and returned to his 1\ndressing room where Dr. Snyder\nand other physicians examined\nhim. He undressed, went to\nbed aad again asked for an\nextra blanket and a hot water\nbottle.\nEats Light Supper\nWith mild sedation, the\nPresident slept until 8 p.m.\nMonday\u2014except during exami\nnations. the physicians re-!\nported. He ate a light supper 1\nin bed and read a Western\nnovel for a half hour. Dr. 1\nSnyder repeated mild sedation!\nand the President slept quietlyi\nI frl n. r mus i$ 1 1\nn#. w mm. 9 frr\nUMNNi 1\n4* fa mvMti it let ftps W\nI \u25a0mrnm, m\ntsESHinVFM STRICKEN tr I\n9 HF\nh\n9\nH IKK HAS A \u201cSTROKE fl\naMcmed\nm, W mh 'tt mm tFW r\n\u25a0I IKK HAS A\n\"land* l\nW~ in at tki I I I\nw if 1\n7 IKE HAS\nSTRflkc\nhis spftrt\n\u25a0ft \"nte* mstm\nBRITISH PRESS REACTION\u2014A collection of the front pages of London\nnewspapers shows how the news of President Eisenhower\u2019s illness was\nreported today.\u2014AP Wirephoto.\nfrom 9 p.m. to 5 a m. yesterday.\n,Mr. Eisenhower stayed in bed\nuntil 7:15 a.m., when he was\nexamined again.\nThe chill probably contrib\nuted to the occlusion, the phy\nsicians said.\nHospitalization would not be\nnecessary, they added.\nTwo additional neurological\nspecialists were called in to\nconsult.\nLeaders View Report\nAsked to elaborate on the\nreport at her midafternoon\npress conference, Mrs. Wheaton\nfirst skid she thought the ill\nness was \u201ca form of heart at\ntack,\u201d but later withdrew this\ncomment. She refused repeat\nedly\u2014even after consulting Dr.\nSnyder by phone\u2014to call the\nillness a stroke. But she later\nsaid it was no form of heart\nattack.\nIn a talk with reporters at\nabout 3:48 p.m. Nfra'Wheaton\nsaid, \"the original diagnosis\n(of occlusion) was made when\nthe President called the doctor\nyesterday (Monday) afternoon\nbetween 3 and 4. As is cus\ntomary, the doctor made a .very\nquick analysis and diagnosis,\nbut wanted to have the full\nfacts of the case before making\nit known to the American\npeople until he was sure\nand had observed the progress.\u201d\nAsked why she had called\nthe illness not serious Monday\nnight, Mrs. Wheaton replied,\n\"that is what I was told\u201d\u2014\nthat she had made her state\nment on the doctors\u2019, advice.\nQuestioned on whethej Sher\nman Adams, presidential as\nsistant, had told her what to\nsay, she replied that \"he knew\nthe statement was being made.\u201d\nSwarm About Nixon\nMr. Nixon was greeted by a|\nswarm of reporters and photog\nraphers when he left the White!\nHouse through the west base\nment entrance at 4:40 pjn..\nafter being Inside from about\n9 a.m.\nThe President was \"fully\ncapable of making major de\ncisions\u201d if necessary, even to\nthe extent of ordering retalia\ntion against an attack on mem\nbers of the North Atlantic\nTreaty Organization, itfr. Nixon\nsaid.\nThere was no need to dele\ngate any of the President\u2019s\npowers to subordinates, he con\ntinued. adding that no major\nproblems requiring Mr. Eisen\nhower\u2019s decision were antici\npated in the next few days.\n\"I can see no decision that\nwould be in any way injurious\nto the President\u2019* health.\u201d he\nsaid.\nUncertain on NATO\nMrs. Wheaton told reporters\nat 4:45 p.m. that the State De\npartment expected the Presi\ndent to miss next month\u2019s\nNATO meeting in Paris. She\nread this statement, issued by\nthe department after consult\ning the White House:\n\"It is to be assumed that\nPresident Eisenhower will not\nattend the NATO meeting in\nf\nMt K\nw .-.V. aM\nsrr fjcitmp sforjf afco\u00bb</ tiny Sor.oton 9 hiring anit In November I fS7,\nedition of RtADKR S DJQEST Thl\u00bb revenltng ttory showt Sonotone leadenhip.\nSONOTONE\n901 WASHINGTON ILDG.\n1435 G St* N.W. Dl. 7-0921\nHsigra,\nCAPT. LORENE MILLER\nPresident\u2019s Nurse\n\u2014AP\u00abMU*\nDecember. Mr. (Paul-Henri)\nSpaak, the secrftagf general,\nhas been asked' to ascemnn\nfrom other <NATO> members\nhow they wish this meeting to\nbe dealt with in the light of\nthis circumstance.\u201d\nMrs. Wheaton told reporters\nat 4:55 p.m. that the military\ndiplomatic reception scheduled\nfor December 3 at the White\nHouse had been postponed.\nShe read excerpts of the\nmedical report for television\ncameras outside the White\nHouse. Stumbling over the\nword \u201ccerebral on her first\ntry, she had to start again.\nChilean\u2019s Visit Off\nAt 5:30 p.m. Mrs. Wheaton\nannounced that the White\nHouse had canceled plans for\na visit by President Ibanez of\nChile scheduled for December\n11-14, but hoped to reschedule\nit later.\nMrs. Wheaton held a press\nconference at 6:15 p.m. to issue\nan optimistic medical bulletin\nby neurological consultants.\nThe confirmed the earlier\ndiagnosis that the President\nhad suffered \u201can occlusion of a\nsmall branch of a cerebral ves\nsel which has produced a slight\ndifficulty in speaking.\u201d which\n\"has improved over the period\nof the last 24 hours and is\nnow manifested only by a hesi\ntancy in saying certain difficult\nwords.\u201d\nThe report was made by Dr.\nFrancis M. Forster, professor of\nneurology and dean of George\ntown University Medical\nSchool: Dr. Houston H. Mer\nritt. professor of neurology at\nColumbia University Medical\nSchool, New York; Dr. James\nF. Hamm ill. assistant professor\nof neurology at Columbia, and\nLt. Col. Roy E. Clausen, jr..\nchief of neurology at Walter\nReed.\nMrs. Wheaton said the con\nsultation lasted an hour and\nthree-quarters.\nShe said the President had\ntalked with \"several people.\u201d\n[and had seen and approved the\nafternoon medical report.\nMrs. Wheaton said she was\nnot sure but assumed the Presi\nI HER SECRET!\nNow you can wear a tiny\nSonotone hearing aid\nCOMPLETELY IN YOU* EAR\nand hear better with ease.\nWeighs only half an\nI 9unce. No cord, nothing\nI worn anywhere except\nin ear. This triumph of\n26-year research is in\nvisible on women, barely\nnoticeable on men.\ndent was still taking anti\ncoagulant medicine, prescribed\nafter his heart attack.\nClaiming the report was\n\u201cclear, concise and needs no\namplification,\u201d she parried\nmost questions and repeatedly\ntried to shut off queries.\nMr. Hagerty arrived at the\nWhite House at 11:10 p.m..\ncalled reporters into his office\nat 11:35 p.m. and told them\n\u201cthe President had a light sup\nper with Mrs. Eisenhower in\nthe family living room.\u201d He re\nported they watched television!\nfrom about 7 p.m. until a little\nafter 9 p.m.\nThe President went to sleep 1\nat 10 p.m., Mr. Hagerty said,!\nand \u201cpresently is sleeping!\nsoundly.\u201d\nHe cleared up a confusing\npoint by reporting Dr. Snyder\nhad not left the White House\nMonday night. At least one\nphysician has been in constant\nattendance since the President\nwas stricken, he added. Dr.\nSnyder left late last night, and\nwas spelled by Col. Tkach, he\nsaid.\nAt 7:10 a.m., he told reporters\nthe President still was sleeping\nHigh officials of the admin\nistration entered and left the\nWhite House through the West\ngate throughout the day yes\nterday, claiming they were at\ntending to such norma) busi\nness as the defense budget.\nDulles on Hand\nVisitors included Secretary of\nState Dulles, who returned in\nthe afternoon after an earlier j\nvisit; Attorney General Rogers,\nwho evaded reporters by having\nhis car sent to a rear door;\nSecretary of Defense McElroy;\nPostmaster General Summer\nfield; Undersecretary*of State\nChristian A. Herter; Deputy\nSecretary of Defense Donald\nA. Quarles; Wilfrid J. McNeil,\nDefense Department controller;\nGeorge V. Allen, director of the\nUnited States Information\nAgency; Arthur Larson, con\nsultant on cold war strategy;\nBudget Director Percival F.\nBrundage, and Dr. Gabriel\nHauge, the President's eco- i\nnomic adviser.\nMr. Allen left at about 2:45\np.m., shortly before the medical\nreport was issued. Apparently\nunder the impression the re\nport already had been released, I\nhe told reporters the situation\nwas \u201cnot terribly alarming.\u201d\nThen he realized he had more\ninformation than the reporters;\nand refused further comment.\nNongovernmental visitors in\ncluded Cyrus Ching, former la\nbor mediator, and Charles E.\nWilson, former head of General i\nElectric, who said they were at\nthe White House to discuss the\n\"people-to-people\" program of\nforeign contacts.\ntoe a smart santa\nMcLachlen\nBanking Corporation\nmain orricintoTH ano o staeits noatmwest\nSOUTHWEST BAANCM IITH ANO MAAVLANO AVt SW\nnOTOMAC PLAZA BNANCM 2428 VIAOINIA AVI N W\nOtrtfti Cost- Yfdera 1 \u2022tv#\n\u2022\u2022SINCE ISSI. A NAME YOU CAN SANK ON\"\nIllness Points Up Need\nFor 'Disability' Action\nContinued From First Page!\ndecided\u2014that there is sufficient;\n\u201cinability\u201d to warrant assump\ntion of the presidency by the\nVice President?\nIssue Raised in 1787\nThe question is older than\nthe Constitution. Delegate John\nDickinson of Delaware raised it\nat the Constitutional Conven\ntion in Philadelphia in 1787,\nbut it was left hanging for fu\nture officials, students and oth\ners to ponder should occasion\narise.\nThe very rarity of such occa-j\nsions has been one reason why\nCongress has done so little,\nabout it. The standard exam-'\npies of the past are those of\nPresidents Garfield and Wil\nson. President Oarfield lay for\n80 days stricken by an assas\nsin\u2019s bullet, During that time\nhis only performance of official\nduty was to sign an extradition 1\npaper. He was too ill even to\nbe asked to make decisions. His\ncabinet was reluctant to ask\nVice President Arthur to do\nanything.\nThe Wilson Case\nFrom September, 1919. to\nMarch, 1921, when his term\nended, President Wilson was\npartly paralyzed. For a time he\nwas so ill that he could not be\nseen by Government officials.\nSome 28 acts of Congress be\ncame law without his signature.\nThere was discussion of the\npossibility and propriety of\nhaving Vice President Marshall\ntake a more active part, the\nnature of which was a matter\nof uncertainty and contro\nversy. Mr. Marshall made no\nmove.\nPresident Eisenhower\u2019s heart\nattack in September, 1955, and\nthe ileitis operation brought\nan open and often frank dis\ncussion in legislative and exec\nutive branch circles as to the\ndesirability of coming to grips\nwith the problem of presidential\ndisability once and for all.\nMr. Eisenhower made clear\nthat his decision whether to\nseek a second term would de\npend largely on whether he felt\nhe would be physically able to\nhandle the burdens of the pres\nidency. He indicated he might\nstep down before the comple\ntion of his first term if his con\ndition approached any inca\npacitation.\nWhen he eventually an\nnounced his candidacy for re\nj nomination he said he was\nsatisfied that he could perform\nessential duties of the office!\nand that sdfne of the lesser bur\ndens could properly be eased\ni by his staff.\nStudy Begun In Congress\nj. The Senate in 1956 un\nanimously passed a resolution\ni for a joint Senate-House com\nmittee study of all questions\nrelating to the office of Presi\ndent and Vice President. This\ncommittee was to study also the\nquestion of who is to determine\nwhen a President is unable to\nperform his constitutional\nduties.\nThat resolution died in the\nHouse Judiciary Committee.\nChairman Celler, Democrat of\nNew York, said he feared lt\nwould provoke partisan debate\nand other bitterness if brought\nup in the presidential election\nyear.\nLast May, however, a special\nsubcommittee headed by Mr.\nCeller voted to have the full\nJudiciary Committee decide on\nthe kind of presidential dis\nability legislation.\nGet Eisenhower Plan\nThat subcommittee showed\nlittle enthusiasm for the plan\npresented by Mr. Eisenhower\nlast March and defended by\nthe then Attorney General\nBrownell at the committee\nhear tog. Speaker Rayburn was\namong many legislators who\nshowed little enthusiasm for\nthe plan.\n\u201cIf the President shall de\nclare in writing that he is\nunable to discharge the powers\nand duties of his office.\u201d the\nEisenhower proposal stated.\u201d\nsuch powers and duties shall be\ndischarged by the Vice Presi\ndent as Acting President. If\nthe President does not so de\nclare, the Vice President, if\nsatisfied of the President\u2019s\ninability would become Acting\nPresident on receiving approval\nm writing from a majority of\nthe Cabinet. Whenever the\nPresident declared in writing\nROOFING\nOver 60,000 RooH in Hit Mttro\npoliton Arts Sine# 1892.\nRose Brothers\nJA. 2-1223\n19th St N 8 ft Mytr Or., Art Vo\nthat his inability is terminated,\n{the President, shall forthwith\nresume the powers and duties\nof qfflee.\u201d\nTruman Offered Proposal\nFormer President Truman\nlast June offered one of the\nfullest and frankest comments\n\u2014but by no means the last\nword\u2014on what he termed the\n\u201cdelicate and sensitive prob\nlem.\u201d He recalled that he, him\nself, became \"acutely conscious\niof the problem in a personal\nway\u201d when President Roosevelt\nreturned from Yalta.\nAfter succeeding to the Presi\ndency at the death of Mr.\n1 Roosevelt, Mr. Truman con\nsidered setting up a commission\nj to make recommendations. War\niand reconstruction brought so\nmany more immediate and\nurgent problems that Mr. Tru\nman\u2019s only specific proposal\nwas for a statute changing the\nsuccession. Under that new law\nthe Speaker of the House and\nPresident Pro Tem. of the Sen\nate rather than Cabinet officers\nare next in line after the Vice\nPresident.\nCalled it Workable\nIn his copyrighted article\ndistributed by North American\nNewspaper Alliance, Mn Tru\nman suggested the following\n\u201cworkable solution\u201d in event\na President is stricken by an\nillness or injury likely to pre\nvent him from performing of\nficial duties:\nA seven-member committee\nmade up of the Vice President.\nChief Justice, the Speaker, and\nmajority and minority leaders\nof House and Senate would se\nlect a board of medical au\nthorities to make necessary ex\naminations and findings.\nThe seven-member commit\ntee, if informed by the medical\nbogrd that a President was\n\u201ctruly incapacitated,\u201d wouM\nnotify Congress which then, by\na two-thirds vote of the full\nmembership, could declare the\nVice President as President.\nThe Vice President, so desig\nnated, would serve out the re\nmainder of the term of the in\ncapacitated President. The\ncommittee could call Congress\ninto special session for such a\npurpose.\nWhen a Vice President suc\nceeded to the Presidency under\nthose circumstances the va\ncancy in the office of. the Vice\nPresident would be filled by\ncalling, together the last Elec\ntoral College. The electors\nwould select) and declare a new\n[Vice President.\nMr. Truman felt that this\nprocedure could be enacted into\nlaw by congressional statute.\nHe said the provisions could be\nframed into a constitutional\n.amendment if necessary. But\nhe added that \u2019\u2019there is always\ngreat danger in writing too\nmuch into the Constitution.\u201d\nA legislative enactment, he said,\nwould provide \u201cgreater flexi\nbility to meet changing condi\ntions.\u201d\nHoover\u2019s View\nFormer President Hoover, re\nplying to a questionnaire sent\nto more than 60 prominent citi\nzens and jurists, told the House\ncommittee last year:\n\u201cIt is my understanding that\nunder Article IT, Section I of\nthe Constitution, the Congress\n\u25a0\u25a0\u25a0HKMBr sat i\nI\nImported Broadcloth *8 to moaauro;\n*3 more buys a whole year\u2019s supply j\nOur shirt* average 75c more than ready made* of the\nj same fabric. Since you only wear out four shirt* a year,\n$3 more buys a whole year\u2019* supply. Custom made shifts\nare mt* to make you look better, feel more comfortable,\nand that should be worth twice $3 a year to any rational 9\ndoctor, lawyer or business chief. This week, our Imported\nBroadcloth is 58 to measure. Others 55.95 to 515.\nCastom Shop\n14th St., Car. N. Y. Av*. Alts New Yerk, Chicago, Phils. 9\nWatch for Our Silver Spring Opening\na'gift from\nBeckers\nmeans more\n1314 F STREET\ns\nnext to a personal valet\nFlashlight\nVacuum wMW\nClever, portable, compact, J laL\nplastic Vacolite whisks away i|*j|\ndust and lint.\nA flashlight-vacuum that\nbrushes and \"bags\" dirt from 11\nyour clothes at a twinkling If\nof an eye. v\nBattery powered \u2014a must SOSO\nJn car or at home. /Ov\n\u25a0STTCeiIS\nMl |N|B\nf ixtrs Very\nOpen a fssrrslnd lndfct mr Charge Arcsmt\nSORRY, NO C.O.D.'J, PLEAS!\nA ft\nTHE EVENING STAR\nWashington, D. C.\nwgwwas\u00dfAT. xovsanaa n, iw\nhas the power to determine who\nshall take over the Executive\npowers in ease of the inability\nof the President to serve- In\nmy view, the determinatioji of\nthe disability and its termina\ntion should rest with the Cabi\nnet, and the Executive powers\nshould be executed by the Vice\nPresident during any such\nperiod.\u201d\nThe complexity of the prob\nlem of defining presidential in\nability or disability was Evi\ndent in the wide range of \u00abtber\nreplies to that questionnaire.\nBeside the problem of physical\nor mental illness, there could\nbe such things as Injury of a\nPresident in an H-bomb at\ntack. his capture in war. kid\nnapping by foreign enemies or\ndomestic gangsters, perhaps\ntemporary disappearance in a\nplane crash, and similar dis\nasters.\nAdvised Against Haste\nA significant feature of the\nquestionnaire replies was that\nI few of the political and other\nexperts cared to frame a defi\nnition. Many of them advised\nCongress to make haste slowly\nlln enacting definitions that\nj might be sufficiently flexible\n;and do more harm than good.\nIndividual Members of Con\ngress have submitted numerous\nand widely varying bills on\nthe subject. Mr. Celler\u2019s pro\nposed congressional enactment\nwould permit a Vice President\non his own initiative to declare\na \"President unable to exercise\nduties. The Vice President\nthen would take oyer the duties\nas Acting President. He said\nhe believed a Vice President\nwould not abuse such discretion\nbut would be guided by a sense\nof responsibility and respect for\npublic opinion.\nRepresentative Keating, of\nNew York, ranking Republican\non the House Judiciary Com\nmittee, has sponsored a bill\nwhereby determination of dis\nability would be made by a\n10-member commission repre\nsenting the three branches of\nthe Government. Still other\nbills call for constitutional\namendments and for presiden\ntial disability determinations by\njthe Supreme Court or outside\ncommission.\njfftinTH\n(ONSUMERt\nI 1413 NEW YORK AVI.\nME. 8-4840\nA-5","height":"28374","width":"18089"}}
